Securitisation
DESCRIPTION: Securitisation is the issuance of debt securities for which coupon or principal payments are backed by specified assets or by future income streams.

NAME: Asset-backed security (ABS)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a pool of assets, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner; excluding mortgages.

NAME: Auto loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Consumer loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Credit card receivables ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Equipment leases ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Home equity loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Manufactured housing leases ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Student loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Whole Business Securitisation (WBS) ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Mixed ABS
DESCRIPTION: An ABS that is a mix of different ABS types, e.g. combination of auto and consumer loans.

NAME: Other Assets ABS
DESCRIPTION: An ABS that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: ABS - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a ABS, but the type is unknown.

NAME: Mortgage-backed security (MBS)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a pool of mortgages, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner.

NAME: Residential mortgage-backed security (RMBS)
DESCRIPTION: Detailed asset type breakdown of MBSs mainly in accordance

NAME: Commercial mortgage-backed security (CMBS)
DESCRIPTION: with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Mixed MBS
DESCRIPTION: An MBS that is a mix of different MBS types, e.g. combination of RMBS and CMBS.

NAME: Other MBS
DESCRIPTION: An MBS that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: MBS - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a MBS, but the type is unknown.

NAME: Collateralised Debt Obligation (CDO)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a diversified pool of loan and bond instruments, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner; excluding mortgages.

NAME: Collateralised Mortgage Obligation (CMO)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a diversified pool of loan and bond instruments of mortgages, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner.

NAME: Mixed securitisation
DESCRIPTION: A securitisation that is a mix of different securitisation types, e.g. combination of auto loans and mortgages.

NAME: Other securitisation
DESCRIPTION: A securitisation that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Securitisation - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a securitisation, but the type is unknown.

NAME: Covered Bond
DESCRIPTION: Covered bonds are debt securities issued by a financial corporation, or fully guaranteed by a financial corporation. In case of default of the issuing or guarantor financial corporation, bond holders have a priority claim on the cover pool, in addition to their ordinary claim on the financial corporation.

NAME: Public sector Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Detailed asset type breakdown of covered bonds mainly in accordance with definitions of European Covered Bond Council.

NAME: Mortgage Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Detailed asset type breakdown of covered bonds mainly in accordance with definitions of European Covered Bond Council.

NAME: Ship Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Detailed asset type breakdown of covered bonds mainly in accordance with definitions of European Covered Bond Council.

NAME: Aircraft Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Detailed asset type breakdown of covered bonds mainly in accordance with definitions of European Covered Bond Council.

NAME: Mixed Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: A covered bond that is a mix of different covered bond types.

NAME: Other Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: A covered bond that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Covered Bond - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a covered bond, but the type is unknown.

NAME: Securitisation and Covered Bond - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a securitistion or covered bond, but the type is not known.

1250% for positions not subject to any method
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions to which a risk weight of 1250% is assigned in accordance with Article 259(1)(d) of CRR.

NAME: SEC-IRBA: Internal ratings-based approach for securitisation positions
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Internal ratings-based approach is used.

NAME: SEC-SA: Standardised approach for securitisations
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Standardised approach is used.

NAME: SEC-ERBA: External ratings-based approach for securitisation positions
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the External ratings-based approach is used.

NAME: Ratings based method
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Ratings based method set out in Article 261 of CRR is used.

NAME: Supervisory formula method
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Supervisory formula method set out in Article 262 of CRR is used.

NAME: IRB: Slotting approach for specialised lending
DESCRIPTION: Holdings other than securitisations or equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for specialised lending exposures subject to the supervisory slotting approach where risk weights are assigned to the exposures

NAME: Internal assessment approach
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Internal assessment approach set out in Article 259(3) and (4) of CRR is used.

NAME: Look-through approach
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Look-through approach set out in Article 259(1)(e) of CRR is used.

NAME: IRB: Internal models approach
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures for which the Internal models approach set out in Article 155(4) of CRR is used.

NAME: IRB: PD/LGD approach
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures for which the PD/LGD approach set out in Article 155(3) of CRR is used.

NAME: IRB: Simple risk weight approach
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures for which the Simple risk weight approach set out in Article 155(2) of CRR is used.

NAME: Standardised approach
DESCRIPTION: Standardised approach to calculate the risk-weighted exposure amounts in accordance with Chapter 2 of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013

NAME: IRB: Advanced approach
DESCRIPTION: Internal Ratings Based (IRB) approach to calculate the risk-weighted exposure amounts in accordance with Chapter 3 of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013 and banks calculate and use, in addition to the PDs, their own risk parameter subject to the supervisory guidelines

NAME: IRB: Foundation approach
DESCRIPTION: Internal Ratings Based (IRB) approach to calculate the risk-weighted exposure amounts in accordance with Chapter 3 of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013 and banks use their own-calculated PDs, while for the other parameters (such as LGD) predefined values provided by supervisors are taken

NAME: IRB: Fixed risk weights
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures which attract a fixed risk weight treatment (without however being explicitly treated according to the Simple Risk Weight approach or the (temporary or permanent) partial use of the credit risk standardised approach) set out in Article 155 of CRR.

DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is subject to impairment in accordance with an applied accounting standard and is collectively assessed for impairment by being grouped together with instruments with similar credit risk characteristics.

NAME: General allowances (GAAP)
DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is subject to impairment in accordance with an applied accounting standard other than IFRS 9 and no specific loss allowances are raised against the instrument (unimpaired).

NAME: Stage 1 (IFRS)
DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is not impaired and a loss allowance at an amount equal to 12-month expected credit losses is raised against the instrument under IFRS. Only for instruments subject to impairment under IFRS 9.

NAME: Stage 2 (IFRS)
DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is not impaired and a loss allowance at an amount equal to lifetime expected credit losses is raised against the instrument under IFRS. Only for instruments subject to impairment under IFRS 9.

NAME: Stage 3 (IFRS)
DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is impaired and a loss allowance at an amount equal to lifetime expected credit losses is raised against the instrument under IFRS. Only for instruments subject to impairment under IFRS 9.

NAME: Specific allowances (GAAP)
DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is subject to impairment in accordance with an applied accounting standard other than IFRS 9 and specific loss allowances are raised, irrespective of whether these allowances are individually or collectively assessed (impaired).

NAME: Debt
DESCRIPTION: Debt securities are negotiable financial instruments serving as evidence of a debt. They are covered by the financial assets and liabilities (financial instrument) category â€œdebt securitiesâ€ (F.3) in ESA 2010.

NAME: Bond
DESCRIPTION: Bonds and debentures are long-term debt securities that give the holders the unconditional right to fixed payments or contractually determined variable payments on a specified date or dates, that is, the earning of interest is not dependent on earnings of the debtors. Bonds and debentures also give holders the unconditional right to fixed sums as payments to the creditor on a specified date or dates.

NAME: Straight bond
DESCRIPTION: A bond without any further special characteristics listed separately.

NAME: Securitisation bond
DESCRIPTION: Securitisation is the issuance of debt securities for which coupon or principal payments are backed by specified assets or by future income streams.

NAME: Traditional securitisation
DESCRIPTION: In case of traditional securitisation, the transfer of credit risk takes place by transferring the assets subject to that risk.

NAME: Synthetic securitisation
DESCRIPTION: In case of synthetic securitisation, the transfer of credit risk takes place by means of instruments that provide insurance against credit losses, without an actual transfer of assets taking place.

NAME: Other securitisation
DESCRIPTION: A securitisation that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Covered bonds are debt securities issued by a financial corporation, or fully guaranteed by a financial corporation. In case of default of the issuing or guarantor financial corporation, bond holders have a priority claim on the cover pool, in addition to their ordinary claim on the financial corporation.

NAME: Jumbo covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Jumbo covered bonds are covered bonds issued in accordance with the requirements in Article 52(4) of Directive 2009/65/EC and with an issuing volume of at least EUR 1 billion, for which at least three market-makers provide regular bid and ask quotes.

NAME: Other covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Covered bonds other than jumbo covered bonds.

NAME: Medium-term note
DESCRIPTION: A debt security issued at fixed or floating rates of interest, as part of an overall medium-term note programme. Used by institutions as a source for medium-term funding.

NAME: Euro medium term notes (EMTN)
DESCRIPTION: A medium-term note denominated in Euro.

NAME: Other MTN
DESCRIPTION: A medium-term note denominated in a currency other than Euro.

NAME: Perpetual bond
DESCRIPTION: A debt security that has no stated maturity date.

NAME: Linked bond
DESCRIPTION: Linked bonds have their coupon or principal payments (or both) linked to a general price index for goods and services (such as the consumer price index (CPI)), interest rate (such as the London interbank offered rate (LIBOR) or a bond yield), or asset price.

NAME: Inflation-linked bond
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns by type in accordance with definitions laid down in Handbook of Securities Statistics.

NAME: Interest rate-linked bond
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns by type in accordance with definitions laid down in Handbook of Securities Statistics.

NAME: Asset-linked bond

DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns by type in accordance with definitions laid down in Handbook of Securities Statistics.

NAME: Strip bond
DESCRIPTION: Separate trading of registered interest and principal of securities (STRIPS) are securities that have been transformed from a principal amount and periodic coupons into a series of zero-coupon bonds, with the range of maturities matching the coupon payment dates and the redemption date of the principal amount.

NAME: Principal strip
DESCRIPTION: A strip bond created for the part of the principal amount.

NAME: Coupon strip
DESCRIPTION: A strip bond created for the part of the coupons.

NAME: Structured debt security (Certificates)
DESCRIPTION: Structured debt securities typically combine a debt security, or a basket of debt securities, with a financial derivative, or a basket of financial derivatives. These financial derivatives are typically embedded in and are therefore inseparable from the debt securities.

NAME: Investment product
DESCRIPTION: The Investment product category of Structured debt securities covers securities where the principal amount is (1) protected and returned at maturity, regardless of the performance of the reference financial instrument; (2) exposed to losses limited to less than the full principal; (3) fully at risk subject to a level of initial loss protection or (4) fully at risk.

NAME: Capital protection product
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Yield enhancement product
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Participation product
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Other investment product
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Leverage Product
DESCRIPTION: The leverage product category of Structured debt securities covers securities with a large risk compared with the initial investment and that combine an investment in an underlying security with a future or option. Detailed breakdowns of upper category in

NAME: Leverage product with knock-out
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Leverage product without knock-out
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Constant leverage product
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Other leverage product
DESCRIPTION: Detailed breakdowns of upper category in accordance with categoristion of European Structured Investment Products Association (EUSIPA).

NAME: Other bond
DESCRIPTION: A bond that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Money market instrument
DESCRIPTION: Money market instruments in accordance with Directive 2009/65/EC comprise transferable instruments which are normally dealt in on the money market rather than on the regulated markets.

NAME: Bankers acceptance
DESCRIPTION: A negotiable order to pay a specified amount of money on a future date, accepted and guaranteed by a bank and drawn on a deposit at a bank.

NAME: Certificate of deposit
DESCRIPTION: Usually a negotiable certificate issued by a bank acknowledging a deposit in that bank for a specified period of time at a specified interest rate.

NAME: Commercial paper
DESCRIPTION: A discounted and unsecured debt security issued by a corporation whose name appears on the front of the security and who promises to pay to the security holder a certain amount on a stated maturity date.

NAME: Euro commercial paper (ECP)
DESCRIPTION: A commercial paper denominated in Euro.

NAME: Pagares
DESCRIPTION: Specific type of commercial paper commonly known in Spain.

NAME: Other CP
DESCRIPTION: A commercial paper that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Treasury bill
DESCRIPTION: A common form of sovereign shortterm debt security that many governments issue. It gives the holder the unconditional right to receive stated fixed sums on a specified date, and is issued at a discount to face value that depends on the rate of interest and the time to maturity.

NAME: Other money market instrument
DESCRIPTION: A money market instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Hybrid debt instrument
DESCRIPTION: Instrument with characteristics of debt and equity which are classified as debt according to their main characteristics.

NAME: Convertible bond
DESCRIPTION: A fixed interest rate bond that the investor has the option of converting into the equity of the borrower or its parent.

NAME: Contingent convertible bonds (CoCoâ€™s)
DESCRIPTION: Contingent convertible securities are hybrid securities issued as debt instruments and automatically converted into equity shares if a contractually pre-defined 'trigger event' occurs. Their defining characteristics are a loss-absorption mechanism (conversion or write-down) and an activation trigger, either based on a mechanical rule or on supervisorsâ€™ discretion.

NAME: Bonds with warrants attached
DESCRIPTION: Bonds with warrants attached are debt securities that incorporate warrants giving the holder the option to purchase equity in the issuer or another company during a predetermined period, or at a particular date, and at a fixed contract price. The warrant may be detachable and traded separately from the debt security.

NAME: Stapled debt instrument
DESCRIPTION: Stapled instruments - which, under their terms of issue, are two or more different financial instruments (for example, ordinary equity securities and unsecured notes) coupled together for certain purposes - are usually treated separately as fixed interest rate debt securities and equity securities. However, stapled instruments usually cannot be transferred separately either in the market or as the result of an over-the-counter (OTC) transaction. A parcel consisting of one equity security and one or more notes is traded in the market as though it were a single security, although conceptually the components are regarded as separate. If the components cannot be separately identified, the stapled instrument should be classified according to the predominant component, that is, either as a debt security or an equity security.

NAME: Non-participating (preferred) share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are entitled to receive a fixed dividend, but do not participate in the distribution of the residual value of a corporation on dissolution.

NAME: Other hybrid debt Instrument
DESCRIPTION: A hybrid debt instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Other debt
DESCRIPTION: A debt instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Equity
DESCRIPTION: Equity securities are negotiable financial instruments that entitle holders to a share of both distributed profits and the residual value of the corporationâ€™s assets in the event of its liquidation. Holders of these financial assets are the collective owners of a corporation. Equity securities are part of the financial assets and liabilities (financial instrument) category â€œequity and investment fund shares or unitsâ€ (F.5) and belong to the subcategory â€œequityâ€ (F.51) in ESA 2010.

NAME: Ordinary / Common share
DESCRIPTION: Ordinary shares (or â€œcommonâ€ shares) usually give holders the right to the following: â€¢ Holders are generally entitled to participate in the corporationâ€™s general policymaking and have the right to attend, speak, and vote (in the case of voting shares) at general meetings. Holders of ordinary shares can vote on corporate objectives and matters of policy, on stock splits, and to elect the corporationâ€™s board of directors. â€¢ Holders are usually entitled to a preferential subscription in the event of a capital increase. Some holders of ordinary shares also receive preemptive rights (a rights issue), which enables them to retain their proportional share in the ownership of a corporation should it issue more stock. â€¢ Holders generally have the right to a share in the corporationâ€™s profits. However, no fixed dividends are paid out to ordinary shareholders. Ordinary shareholdersâ€™ returns are therefore uncertain and dependent on earnings, corporate reinvestment, and the marketâ€™s ability to value and sell stock efficiently.

NAME: Preference / Preferred share
DESCRIPTION: Holders of preferred shares have priority over holders of ordinary shares when it comes to laying claim to a corporationâ€™s assets. However, while preferred shares may have priority over ordinary shares in the payment of dividends and in the event of liquidation, they are subordinated to debt securities.

NAME: Cumulative preferred share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are entitled to receive a fixed dividend ahead of ordinary shares and retain the right to any accumulated preferred dividends that may have built up.

NAME: Participating preferred share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are entitled to participate in the profits of a corporation over and above fixed dividends by means of an additional fluctuating dividend. They also participate in the distribution of the residual value of a corporation on dissolution.

NAME: Cumulative, participating preferred share
DESCRIPTION: A preferred share that fulfils the criteria of cumulative and participating preferred shares at the same time.

NAME: Redeemable preferred share
DESCRIPTION: These can be redeemed at the request of either the corporation or the shareholder (at a fixed price on a specified date or during a specified period of time). Strict conditions apply to the issuance of redeemable shares and their redemption. Instead of cancelling shares on redemption, a corporation may continue to hold such shares as treasury shares, but no voting rights may be exercised and no dividends are payable.

NAME: Other preferred share
DESCRIPTION: A prefered share that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Depository receipt
DESCRIPTION: A financial instrument that allows a nonresident to introduce securities into a market in a form more readily acceptable to the investors in that market. A deposit-taking corporation will purchase the underlying security and then issue receipts in a currency more acceptable to the investor.

NAME: American depository receipt (ADR)
DESCRIPTION: American depository receipts (ADR) are liabilities of the non-U.S. institutional units whose securities underlie the ADR, not of the U.S. financial institutions issuing the ADR.

NAME: Global depository receipt (GDR)
DESCRIPTION: Global depository receipts (GDR) are securities available in one or more markets outside the corporationâ€™s country of residence.

NAME: Other depository receipt
DESCRIPTION: A depository receipt that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Hybrid equity instrument
DESCRIPTION: Instrument with characteristics of debt and equity which are classified as equity according to their main characteristics.

NAME: Participation certificate (Genussschein)
DESCRIPTION: Participation certificates grant their holders participation rights. Participation rights may take various forms, both for equity securities and for debt securities. In many countries, almost no legal restrictions are placed on this type of financial instrument. Depending on their specific features, participation certificates are considered to be either equity securities or debt securities. They are treated as equity securities if the following criteria are met: a) the holderâ€™s claims are subordinated, b)the holderâ€™s remuneration is performance related and c) capital is provided for an unlimited period, or at least on a long-term basis. In light of these criteria, most participation certificates are considered to be equity securities. 3.47 â€œGenussscheineâ€ (or â€œGenussrechteâ€) are a type of participation certificate. These are issued mainly in European countries such as Germany, Austria, and Switzerland. â€œGenussscheineâ€ sometimes have a stated maturity.

NAME: Convertible (preferred) share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are allowed to convert preferred shares into a specified amount of ordinary shares.

NAME: Subscription right
DESCRIPTION: Subscription rights that are traded separately are often given their own separate International Securities Identification Number (ISIN). They are classified as shares, rather than as financial derivatives, since they represent a claim on the residual value of a corporation. Issuers of shares use subscription rights to provide existing shareholders with the opportunity to participate in new issues, which enables them to retain their proportional share in the ownership of the corporation. To make the new shares even more attractive, these subscription rights may also allow existing shareholders to buy the shares at less than the market price.

NAME: Other hybrid equity instrument
DESCRIPTION: A hybrid equity instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Other equity
DESCRIPTION: An equity instrument that is of a type not listed separately. This also includes "Other equity" in accordance with ESA 2010 (F.519) that is not in the form of securities. Other equity includes equity in quasi-corporations (such as branches, trusts, and partnerships), as well as notional units representing ownership of real estate.

NAME: Fund
DESCRIPTION: Investment fund shares are shares of an investment fund if the fund has a corporate structure. They are known as units if the fund is a trust. Investment funds are collective investment undertakings through which investors pool funds for investment in financial and/or non-financial assets. Funds are part of the financial assets and liabilities (financial instrument) category â€œequity and investment fund shares or unitsâ€ (F.5) and belong to the subcategory â€œInvestment fund shares or unitsâ€ (F.52) in ESA 2010.

NAME: Undertaking for collective investment in transferable securities (UCITS) Fund
DESCRIPTION: Undertakings for Collective Investment in Transferable Securities (UCITS) as defined in Directive 2009/65/EC on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to UCITS.

NAME: Alternative investment fund (AIF)
DESCRIPTION: Alternative investment fund (AIF) as defined in Directive 2011/61/EU on Alternative Investment Fund Managers.

NAME: Other fund
DESCRIPTION: A fund that is of a type not listed separately.

not alive - not covered by IF list
